606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9957863688468933, "span": {"begin": 448, "end": 453}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000782"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "aneuploid", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9872177243232727, "span": {"begin": 467, "end": 476}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human oocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8724687695503235, "span": {"begin": 583, "end": 596}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.8343120217323303, "span": {"begin": 583, "end": 588}}, {"id": ["mim:190685", "mesh:D004314"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Trisomy 21", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999969005584717, "span": {"begin": 726, "end": 736}}, {"id": ["mim:190685", "mesh:D004314"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Down syndrome", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999994039535522, "span": {"begin": 740, "end": 753}}, {"id": ["mesh:D030342"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "genetic abnormality", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999990463256836, "span": {"begin": 811, "end": 830}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9803670644760132, "span": {"begin": 883, "end": 888}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000782"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "aneuploidy", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9968720078468323, "span": {"begin": 889, "end": 899}}], "text": "Aneuploidy arising during meiosis in germ cells represents the most common chromosomal abnormality at birth and is the leading cause of pregnancy loss in humans. The presence of aneuploid eggs in humans ranges (depending on age), but is approximately 20%. In parallel, approximately 10&ndash;30% of human zygotes are aneuploid. 50% of human pregnancies are spontaneously aborted; of these, 50% are due to aneuploidy. Finally, approximately 0.3% of human newborns are aneuploid. These data are summarized in Hassold et al. [2007] and Nagaoka et al. [2012]. It is widely accepted that human oocytes are particularly susceptible to chromosome mis-segregation [Hassold et al., 2007; Hunt and Hassold, 2002; Nagaoka et al., 2012]. Trisomy 21 or Down syndrome, with an occurrence of ~1/720 births, is the most common genetic abnormality in newborns [Hassold et al., 2007]. The etiology of human aneuploidy is still not well understood, although there is strong evidence supporting a preferential occurrence during female meiosis I and a positive correlation with maternal age [Hunt and Hassold, 2002; Nagaoka et al., 2012; Webster and Schuh, 2017].  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:48:33 +0000 2026"}